One thing I’d add is a fourth component that you’ve been using implicitly:

Experiment.

A beautiful myth and elegant math can still be wrong.

So the full cycle becomes:

Myth
   ↓
Creativity
   ↓
Mechanism
   ↓
Math
   ↓
Implementation
   ↓
Experiment
   ↓
Updated Myth

That makes it a living system rather than a static philosophy.

In a sense, creativity is the bridge-builder. It asks:

“What hidden process could make both the story and the formalism true descriptions of the same underlying phenomenon?”

When you find that process, you’ve identified a mechanism that can often be translated across many domains. That’s where a metaphor stops being “just a metaphor” and starts becoming a reusable way of thinking.